{"key":"post-8624523","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8624523</id>\n<content>Personally, I hate the cheap(under $1000) microscopes.&amp;nbsp;  Their optics suck.&amp;nbsp; You might look for lab auctions and the like to find a quality microscope used.&amp;nbsp; The cheap ones only advertise the magnification, but much more important is the size and qualty of the objectives.&amp;nbsp; I actually use my zoom microscope with a maximum magnification of 50X far more often than my light microscopes.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;However, for new growers getting started, a far more important big purchase is a laminar flow hood.&amp;nbsp; A good flowhood will negate the need for a microscope until you get really geeky and want to study cell structure, look at clamp connections, and count the nuclei in a cell.&amp;nbsp; I don't even bother trying to use my microscopes to ID contaminants.&amp;nbsp; You can isolate away from contamination with the naked eye to clean up a culture, but you'll need agar supplies and at least a good glovebox, but a flowhood is preferred.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>8623485</prev>\n<first>8620103</first>\n<last>8624523</last>\n<when>1215870097</when>\n<utime>07/12/08 04:41 PM</utime>\n</post>"}